[2] Cholera - Israel: water reservoir contamination
Date: Fri 11 Nov 2022
Source: Government of Israel [in Hebrew, trans., edited]
https://www.gov.il/he/departments/news/11112022-01


On 11 Nov 2022 the Israel Ministry of Health announced that cholera was detected in a Yarmoukim reservoir in northern Israel. The reservoir is being treated and monitored, and at present the public is not at risk for an outbreak and this does not presently pose a danger to the population. The reservoir has been cut off from flowing to the Kinneret (Sea of Galilee), a major fresh water body for the country, and the water was being chlorinated and monitored. The Yarmouk River runs through Syria, and this is believed to be the source of the contamination, as there has been a significant cholera outbreak in that region.

Due to the current outbreak of cholera in southern Syria, the Ministry of Health and Israel Water Authority have been closely monitoring water sources in the north for months. This includes water sources that flow through or are in proximity to Syria and Lebanon. The contaminated sample was found due to early detection systems that were put into place at the beginning of the Syrian outbreak. The Israel Ministry of Health has informed neighboring ministries of health, including Jordan and the Palestinian Authority, with information on steps being taken to control the spread of cholera.

Cholera epidemics ended in Israel at the end of the Ottoman Empire, with the last outbreak in 1970.

--
Communicated by:
Dr. Eliana Aaron DNP
